    "contentMarkdown": "Cross-border payment cost comparisons usually get reduced to a single headline fee — which badly understates what a traditional wire actually costs once every layer is counted. Here's the fuller picture, stablecoins on one side, correspondent banking on the other.\n\n## What a traditional SWIFT wire actually costs\n\nThe fee your bank quotes you is rarely the full cost:\n\n- **Direct transfer fee**: typically **$25–$50** (sending bank charge, corridor-dependent).\n- **FX markup**: **1–3%** on the converted amount — though for some corridors and use cases, FX markup alone accounts for **60–97% of the total cost** of the transfer.\n- **Intermediary bank fees**: **$15–$40 per hop**, and correspondent banking payments frequently route through more than one intermediary bank before reaching the recipient.\n\nAdd it up, and the **true total cost of a traditional cross-border wire runs 2–7%** of the transfer value — far above what the advertised flat fee suggests.\n\n## What businesses report paying over stablecoin rails\n\nBusinesses already using stablecoins for cross-border payments report:\n\n- **Average cost savings of 35%** versus their prior traditional-rail costs.\n- **Up to 47% savings** for companies processing more than **$100 million a month**, where correspondent banking fees compound fastest across high transaction volume.\n- The two most-cited reasons for switching: **lower transaction cost (52%)** and **faster settlement (45%)**.\n\n## Why the structural gap exists\n\nCorrespondent banking's cost comes from its architecture: a payment routes through a chain of intermediary banks, each taking a cut and adding settlement time, before reaching the destination bank. Stablecoin transfers, by contrast, move value across far fewer hops — which is the direct source of both the cost and speed advantage reported by businesses using them.\n\n## The policy backdrop\n\nThis isn't just an industry-vs-industry comparison — regulators are watching the same gap. The **G20 set a target of sub-1% costs for retail cross-border payments and sub-3% for remittances by 2027**. A **December 2025 BIS report** already flagged that traditional-rail improvements alone are unlikely to hit that target on schedule — one reason alternative rails, stablecoins included, are drawing regulatory and institutional attention rather than being dismissed as a niche workaround.\n\n## The practical takeaway\n\nFor a business moving occasional, small cross-border payments, the traditional wire's fixed fees may still be manageable. For businesses with high-frequency, high-volume, or thin-margin cross-border flows — where a 2–7% cost bite recurs on every transfer — the reported 35–47% savings from stablecoin rails represent a real, structural cost difference worth evaluating directly against your specific corridors and volumes.\n\n## Sources\n\nTraditional wire cost data from [BOSS Money's 2026 wire transfer fee guide](https://www.bossmoney.com/en-us/blog/international-wire-transfer-fees) and [Routefusion's cross-border fee breakdown](https://routefusion.com/blog/cross-border-payment-fees). Stablecoin savings data from [Reap Global — Stablecoin Statistics 2026](https://reap.global/blog/stablecoin-statistics-2026)."
