    "contentMarkdown": "Gartner's rolling 2026 IT spending forecasts have been revised upward repeatedly over the past year — a pattern itself worth noting, since it reflects AI infrastructure demand consistently outpacing analyst expectations.\n\n## The topline numbers\n\nGartner's most recent forecast puts **worldwide IT spending growth at 13.5% in 2026**, totaling **$6.31 trillion** — up from earlier-year forecasts of 10.8% and 9.8% growth issued in prior quarters, each successive revision moving higher as actual demand came in stronger than modeled. Within that total, **public cloud end-user spending alone is forecast at $850 billion in 2026**, a **21.3% jump from 2025** — cloud is growing meaningfully faster than IT spending overall.\n\n## Where the growth is concentrated\n\nThe driver is unambiguous: **AI infrastructure and hyperscale cloud demand**. Gartner projects spending on **data center systems** — the servers, networking, and facilities underpinning both cloud and AI workloads — will **surpass $788 billion in 2026**, a figure that reflects the capital intensity of the current AI buildout cycle far more than traditional enterprise IT refresh cycles.\n\n## The sovereign cloud subplot\n\nA smaller but fast-growing category worth tracking separately: **sovereign cloud infrastructure (IaaS) spending**, forecast at **$80 billion globally in 2026**, up **35.6% from 2025** — outpacing even overall public cloud growth. Regionally, **Middle East and Africa (89% growth)**, **mature Asia/Pacific (87%)**, and **Europe (83%)** are projected to post the steepest sovereign cloud growth rates, driven largely by data-residency regulation rather than pure demand economics.\n\n## Why this matters\n\nFor anyone selling into enterprise IT budgets in 2026, the data suggests two distinct growth pools worth targeting separately: the broad AI-infrastructure-driven cloud and data center wave, and a smaller but faster-growing regulatory-driven sovereign cloud segment concentrated outside the US. Forecasters underestimating AI-driven demand repeatedly through 2025–2026 is itself a signal that spending momentum here has outrun typical planning cycles.\n\n## Sources\n\n[Gartner Forecasts Worldwide IT Spending to Grow 13.5% in 2026, Totaling $6.31 Trillion](https://www.gartner.com/en/newsroom/press-releases/2026-04-22-gartner-forecasts-worldwide-it-spending-to-grow-13-point-5-percent-in-2026-totaling-6-point-31-trillion-dollars), [Gartner Says Worldwide Sovereign Cloud IaaS Spending Will Total $80 Billion in 2026](https://www.gartner.com/en/newsroom/press-releases/2026-02-09-gartner-says-worldwide-sovereign-cloud-iaas-spending-will-total-us-dollars-80-billion-in-2026)."
