    "contentMarkdown": "Stripe and Adyen both power payments for some of the world's biggest SaaS and marketplace businesses, but they optimize for different growth stages. The pricing structure you pick can materially change your effective processing cost as volume scales.\n\n## Pricing structure\n\n**Stripe** uses a flat-rate model: 2.9% + $0.30 per successful online card charge in the US, regardless of whether the card is a low-cost debit card or a premium rewards card with higher interchange. It's predictable and requires no negotiation, with T+2 settlement and no monthly minimums.\n\n**Adyen** uses interchange-plus (sometimes called interchange++) pricing, starting from around 0.6% + $0.11, where you pay the actual card-network interchange rate plus Adyen's fixed markup. This is more complex but can be meaningfully cheaper at scale, since you're not subsidizing a blended flat rate.\n\n## Where the crossover happens\n\nIndustry analysis puts the **break-even point between roughly $750K and $1.2M in monthly transaction volume**, depending on card mix and average ticket size. Below that, Stripe generally wins on simplicity and total cost. Above it — particularly for merchants with significant cross-border volume or higher average order values — Adyen's interchange-plus structure starts to pull ahead.\n\n## Chargebacks and platform scope\n\nAdyen charges roughly $7.50 per chargeback dispute, on top of any card-network scheme fees. Stripe's dispute fee structure varies by plan and region. Beyond payments, Adyen also offers a genuinely unified in-store and online platform, which appeals to omnichannel retailers running multiple physical locations alongside e-commerce — an area where Stripe's ecosystem is comparatively newer.\n\n## Which one wins for which use case\n\nEarly-stage and mid-market SaaS or marketplace startups doing most volume online will usually find Stripe's transparency and developer tooling faster to launch with. Larger, multi-channel, or heavily cross-border businesses processing well above $1M a month are the ones for whom negotiating Adyen's interchange-plus terms tends to pay off.\n\n## Sources\n\n[Airwallex: Stripe vs Adyen 2026](https://www.airwallex.com/en-au/blog/comparison-stripe-vs-adyen), [Chargeflow: Stripe vs Adyen 2026](https://www.chargeflow.io/blog/stripe-vs-adyen), [NerdWallet: Adyen vs Stripe 2026](https://www.nerdwallet.com/business/software/learn/adyen-vs-stripe)."
