    "contentMarkdown": "As digital challenger banks mature, the choice between Revolut Business and a traditional high-street bank has shifted from \"risky fintech vs safe incumbent\" to a more genuine trade-off between speed/cost and depth of service.\n\n## Onboarding speed\n\nTraditional bank account opening for an SME often involves **weeks of paperwork** and, in many cases, branch visits. Revolut Business offers **online onboarding that can get a business running in hours**, which is a major draw for fast-moving startups and international founders.\n\n## Foreign exchange cost\n\nThis is where the gap is starkest. Revolut applies roughly a **0.6% FX markup** on most plans once monthly allowances are used, compared with a typical **2-6% spread** at high-street banks — meaning cross-border payments and multi-currency holding are substantially cheaper on Revolut for active international businesses. Revolut Business also lets companies **hold, send, and receive in over 25 currencies** from one account dashboard.\n\n## Regulatory status\n\nA key 2025-2026 shift: Revolut has secured its **UK banking license**, placing it under regulatory oversight comparable to traditional banks, with implications for deposit protection under schemes like the FSCS. This narrows one of the traditional arguments for sticking with an incumbent bank.\n\n## Where traditional banks still win\n\nTraditional banks retain real advantages for SMEs that need **lending relationships, branch access, cash and cheque deposit handling, or high-volume domestic transaction support**. Revolut's tiered plans unlock more features (bulk transfers, cards, integrations) at higher tiers, but fee complexity and limits on lending remain a gap as businesses scale.\n\n## Which one wins for which use case\n\nFast-moving, global-first SMEs prioritizing speed, multi-currency operations, and low FX cost are well served by Revolut Business. Businesses needing deep domestic banking relationships, credit facilities, or physical cash handling still benefit from keeping (or pairing with) a traditional bank account.\n\n## Sources\n\n[Sterlinx Global: Revolut vs Traditional SME Banking](https://sterlinxglobal.com/revolut-vs-traditional-sme-banking-which-is-better-for-your-uk-limited-company/), [European Business Magazine: Best Business Bank Accounts in Europe 2026](https://europeanbusinessmagazine.com/buying-guides/best-business-bank-accounts-in-europe-2026/), [Propicked: Revolut Business Review 2026](https://propicked.com/business/revolut-business)."
