    "contentMarkdown": "Cloud vendor choice for a new startup increasingly comes down to two questions: how much free runway does the credit program buy, and how much does the bill actually cost once you're paying full price. In 2026, the three majors answer both questions differently.\n\n## Startup credit programs\n\n**Google Cloud** leads the pack: equity-funded startups get up to $100,000 in year one (Google covering up to 100% of costs) plus another $100,000 in year two (up to 50% covered). For startups classified as **\"AI-First,\"** Google raised the total 2026 credit ceiling to **up to $350,000**.\n\n**AWS** offers a self-serve $1,000, scaling up to $100,000 for accelerator- or VC-backed startups. New in 2026 is an **AI Tier** worth **$300,000 over 24 months**, aimed specifically at startups training large language models and foundational AI systems.\n\n**Microsoft Azure** has tightened its unfunded-startup tier to just **$5,000**, but investor-backed startups can access **up to $100,000** through its newer Investor Network track. Azure credits also bundle in GitHub Enterprise, Visual Studio Enterprise, and Microsoft 365 access — value beyond raw compute.\n\n## Underlying pricing\n\nCredits aside, for a representative SaaS workload, **Google Cloud pricing runs an estimated 6-10% cheaper** than AWS or Azure, largely due to lower compute and database costs, with the gap widening further as sustained-use discounts accumulate with higher utilization.\n\n## Which one wins for which use case\n\nFor **AI-first startups training or fine-tuning large models**, Google Cloud's $350,000 ceiling and AWS's new $300,000 AI Tier are both worth evaluating directly against each other before committing. For **typical SaaS startups** watching every dollar over a 12-month runway, GCP's combination of credits and lower baseline pricing is the most cost-efficient starting point on paper. Azure remains competitive for startups already standardized on Microsoft tooling (GitHub, VS, M365), where the bundled non-compute value adds up.\n\n## Sources\n\n[TechGenyz: Google Cloud vs AWS vs Azure Startups 2026](https://techgenyz.com/google-cloud-vs-aws-vs-azure-startups-insight/), [CloudKompas: Free Cloud Credits Compared 2026](https://cloudkompas.com/blog/free-cloud-credits-for-startups-AWS-azure-google-cloud-oci), [Culta: Cloud Costs for Startups 2026](https://culta.ai/blog/cloud-infrastructure-costs-startups)."
