    "contentMarkdown": "Bundles like the GitHub Student Developer Pack are marketed as a single free perk, but they're really a verification layer sitting on top of dozens of independent partner deals. Understanding that structure is what separates a smooth signup from a rejected application.\n\n## The verification-gated bundle model\n\nTo even see the offers, an applicant has to prove current enrollment at a degree- or diploma-granting institution (or a K-12 school), using a personal, non-organizational account. GitHub's own documentation ranks proof types by strength: a dated school-issued ID or enrollment letter is treated as strong evidence, while a class schedule, syllabus or student-portal screenshot is treated as weak and more likely to trigger manual review or rejection. Once verified, the \"pack\" itself is not one offer — it's an aggregator of well over 200 separate partner deals (cloud credits, IDE licenses, domain registration, security tools), each governed by that individual company's own terms, not GitHub's. Status isn't permanent either: student validation is generally time-boxed to a couple of years, after which re-verification is required to keep access.\n\n## How to evaluate and verify before relying on it\n\nBefore building a workflow around any bundled tool, check three things: whether the specific partner offer is still listed as active on the official program page (partner lists change over time); whether the partner's own terms restrict the tool to non-commercial or educational use, since running paid client work on a \"student\" license can violate that partner's agreement; and how the offer degrades after graduation or re-verification failure — some tools downgrade to a paid tier automatically, others cut access immediately. Apply directly through the official program site, and treat any third-party site claiming to sell or guarantee \"instant approval\" as a red flag, since legitimate verification cannot be purchased.\n\n## Sources\n\n[GitHub Education - Student Pack](https://education.github.com/pack/join), [Student Developer Pack Partners FAQ](https://github.com/github-education-resources/Student-Developer-Pack-Current-Partners-FAQ)."
