    "contentMarkdown": "Nearly every SaaS pricing page offers a discount for paying annually instead of monthly, and that discount tends to land in a surprisingly consistent band across the industry rather than being picked at random.\n\n## Why the discount clusters around 15-20%\n\nPricing research on SaaS benchmarks points to roughly 15-20% as the sweet spot, most commonly expressed as \"two months free\" on a 12-month term. The logic runs in both directions: too small a discount and the saving doesn't outweigh a buyer's reluctance to commit cash upfront for a full year; too large a discount and it starts to undercut the vendor's own monthly price as the credible reference point, training buyers to see monthly pricing as inflated. The framing choice matters as much as the number — \"get two months free\" tends to outperform \"save 17%\" in conversion even though they describe the same underlying discount, because a concrete quantity (free months) resonates more than an abstract percentage. The real economic driver behind offering any discount at all is churn: annual plans report meaningfully lower yearly churn than monthly plans, so the discount functions as a payment to the vendor's own retention numbers, not pure generosity.\n\n## How to evaluate an annual plan before committing\n\nWork out your own breakeven: if you'd cancel a monthly plan before roughly ten to eleven months of use, the annual discount likely isn't worth the reduced flexibility. Check whether the annual price is locked for the full term or subject to a renewal increase, since some vendors discount year one only. Confirm the refund and downgrade policy if your usage drops mid-term, since annual commitments typically limit how easily you can scale down spending compared to a monthly plan you could simply cancel.\n\n## Sources\n\n[Fungies.io - Annual vs Monthly SaaS Pricing 2026](https://fungies.io/annual-vs-monthly-saas-pricing-strategy/), [InnerTrends - Best Discount for Yearly Subscriptions](https://www.innertrends.com/blog/saas-pricing-strategies)."
